WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.308 --> 00:00:02.891
(upbeat music)

2
00:00:07.890 --> 00:00:09.510
<v David>Dr. Conner is back.</v>

3
00:00:09.510 --> 00:00:14.510
We're gonna be talking about Pulmonary Infections, Part 2.

4
00:00:14.730 --> 00:00:15.840
Okay, Shawn, take it away.

5
00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:16.673
Thank you, sir.
<v ->Thank you, David.</v>

6
00:00:16.673 --> 00:00:19.080
So this one is a little bit more heavy-hitting

7
00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:20.250
than the last one.

8
00:00:20.250 --> 00:00:21.720
Community-acquired pneumonia, like I said,

9
00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:24.120
I think is fairly straightforward.

10
00:00:24.120 --> 00:00:27.540
The pneumococcal recommendations again,

11
00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:32.400
the PCV 21 and done for any condition,

12
00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:34.110
doesn't matter, they don't need a second one,

13
00:00:34.110 --> 00:00:35.340
they never need a second one.

14
00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:37.020
That's how powerful that vaccine is.

15
00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:38.913
Whether they've got a splenectomy,

16
00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:41.670
cochlear implant, doesn't matter.

17
00:00:41.670 --> 00:00:44.340
A CFS, it's all the same.

18
00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.290
So don't overthink that vaccine,

19
00:00:46.290 --> 00:00:47.583
it's very simplified.

20
00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:51.060
This one, we get into a little bit more weeds

21
00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:54.630
because we're discussing some other types of infections

22
00:00:54.630 --> 00:00:58.980
that I guarantee you will show up on the boards,

23
00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:01.470
if not once but multiple times.

24
00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:02.613
First question:

25
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:07.260
A 38-year-old consults you with marked fatigue,

26
00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:11.580
cough, headache, night sweats, and myalgias.

27
00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:14.100
Past medical history is unremarkable.

28
00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:16.920
Social history reveals that they returned

29
00:01:16.920 --> 00:01:19.920
from a summer hiking trip in Arizona two weeks ago.

30
00:01:19.920 --> 00:01:21.888
Now, why the hell did they tell me that?

31
00:01:21.888 --> 00:01:22.721
(audience laughs)

32
00:01:22.721 --> 00:01:24.120
I don't care.

33
00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:26.370
Well, unless you do, right?

34
00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:29.430
So they return from a summer hiking trip in Arizona

35
00:01:29.430 --> 00:01:30.900
two weeks ago, interesting.

36
00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:32.640
Physical examination reveals a fever

37
00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:36.990
of 101 degrees Fahrenheit but is otherwise unremarkable.

38
00:01:36.990 --> 00:01:39.060
Chest x-ray shows nonspecific

39
00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:43.050
left perihilar patchy infiltrate

40
00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:44.910
and their PPD is negative.

41
00:01:44.910 --> 00:01:47.100
These findings are most likely a result of,

42
00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:49.830
A: Histoplasmosis.

43
00:01:49.830 --> 00:01:52.980
B: Coccidioidomycosis,

44
00:01:52.980 --> 00:01:54.600
C: Crytococcosis.

45
00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:57.540
Or D: Tuberculosis.

46
00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:01.350
The key here is there's some piece of information

47
00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:02.910
in the stem of the question

48
00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:05.550
that should lead you down the right path.

49
00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:10.380
And in this case, it is the Southwestern United States,

50
00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:12.930
including the state of Arizona,

51
00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:16.350
and that gives you the answer to the question,

52
00:02:16.350 --> 00:02:20.250
which, of course, is cocci, coccidioidomycosis.

53
00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:24.330
Now, this is an example

54
00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:26.490
of a fungal lung infection.

55
00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:29.940
They always ask fungal lung infections on the boards.

56
00:02:29.940 --> 00:02:31.590
Did y'all hear me?

57
00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:35.220
Always, if not one, multiple.

58
00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:38.610
I had multiple when I took the boards last year.

59
00:02:38.610 --> 00:02:39.750
Which ones they're gonna...

60
00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:42.120
It could be histo, it could be blasto,

61
00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:44.100
it could be cocci.

62
00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.380
I suspect very strongly

63
00:02:46.380 --> 00:02:48.660
that they're going to be cocci-related

64
00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:53.490
because coccidioidomycosis cases are vastly on the rise.

65
00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:54.840
Because of global warming,

66
00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:57.870
we suspect the range has spread significantly

67
00:02:57.870 --> 00:03:01.320
beyond the states that you would normally think about.

68
00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:04.200
The FDA is currently involved in a huge study

69
00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:07.920
about treating this earlier with fluconazole.

70
00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:11.520
There's a whole big video series you can watch

71
00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.070
at the CDC's website about cocci.

72
00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:16.980
So my guess is that's the one you're gonna see

73
00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:18.270
the most questions on,

74
00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:20.760
and that's why I've included the most data.

75
00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:23.130
So fungal lung infections,

76
00:03:23.130 --> 00:03:24.570
they can be opportunistic

77
00:03:24.570 --> 00:03:26.040
in an immunocompromised patient,

78
00:03:26.040 --> 00:03:28.410
that's aspergillosis and candidiasis,

79
00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:29.370
or they're endemic.

80
00:03:29.370 --> 00:03:31.560
That means they're based on the region

81
00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:33.840
where you grew up or you spent time.

82
00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:35.220
They're often asymptomatic.

83
00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:37.830
They may present as community-acquired pneumonia

84
00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:40.170
or they could be incidental findings.

85
00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:42.240
Another common one would be

86
00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:47.190
the multiple BB-sized miliary pattern

87
00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:50.400
on a routine chest X-ray in an asymptomatic patient.

88
00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:52.683
Well, I grew up on a farm in Ohio,

89
00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:58.563
so it's histo in that case, right?

90
00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:02.910
So a lot of it is dependent on the area.

91
00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:04.140
All right, let's move on.

92
00:04:04.140 --> 00:04:05.280
Next question:

93
00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:07.620
Which laboratory result might support

94
00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:10.530
the suspected diagnosis in your 38-year-old patient

95
00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:12.870
presenting with atypical pneumonia?

96
00:04:12.870 --> 00:04:15.840
A: An elevated alkaline phosphatase.

97
00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:19.290
B: An elevated blood eosinophil count

98
00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:22.530
C: An elevated creatinine phosphokinase.

99
00:04:22.530 --> 00:04:25.110
Or D: A macrocytic anemia.

100
00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:27.810
I was asked this exact same question

101
00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:29.100
on the boards last April,

102
00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:31.250
that's why I've included it here for y'all.

103
00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:35.820
So there's a specific laboratory test

104
00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:38.340
that might help aid you in the diagnosis

105
00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:41.700
if you're suspecting a fungal lung infection.

106
00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:42.533
What do we think it is?

107
00:04:42.533 --> 00:04:43.366
Come on folks.

108
00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:47.250
I bet you you'll get this right.

109
00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:49.700
Y'all have been a really smart audience thus far.

110
00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:53.440
<v Respondent>I'm gonna take B.</v>

111
00:04:54.670 --> 00:04:55.830
<v ->Good, that's correct,</v>

112
00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:58.230
an elevated blood eosinophil count may help you.

113
00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:04.380
Next question: "Desert Rheumatism" is a colloquial term

114
00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:07.920
describing a classic triad in coccidioidomycosis

115
00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:10.740
describing fever, myalgias,

116
00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:13.410
and which specific dermatologic finding

117
00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:15.600
of the bilateral lower extremities?

118
00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:18.420
A: Erythema migraines.

119
00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:21.150
B: Erythema multiforme,

120
00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:23.610
C: Erythema nodosum.

121
00:05:23.610 --> 00:05:28.440
Or D: Palpable purpuric papules.

122
00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:31.893
I was asked this question as well on the boards,

123
00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:34.920
and I did not know the answer to it.

124
00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:37.353
So this is a learning opportunity for me.

125
00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:43.470
So desert rheumatism, fever, myalgias,

126
00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:47.010
and a bilateral lower leg dermatologic finding,

127
00:05:47.010 --> 00:05:47.860
what do we think?

128
00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:55.680
Good, y'all are smarter than I was.

129
00:05:55.680 --> 00:05:57.180
I think I guessed right and got it.

130
00:05:57.180 --> 00:05:59.910
But anyway, erythema nodosum is the correct answer.

131
00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:03.390
All right, so we're gonna discuss coccidioidomycosis.

132
00:06:03.390 --> 00:06:05.460
This is, I think, the most likely

133
00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:07.020
to occur on the on the boards,

134
00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:08.820
you can never say exactly.

135
00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:11.280
The cases arising as I said,

136
00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:14.310
symptomatic cases can be up to 40% of the time,

137
00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:17.730
and that will be within the first few weeks after exposure.

138
00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:18.900
In our case, it was two weeks

139
00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:20.290
after his trip to Arizona

140
00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:24.030
with classic symptoms of an atypical pneumonia.

141
00:06:24.030 --> 00:06:25.050
Most of them recover,

142
00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:29.160
but some move on to develop chronic lung diseases.

143
00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:30.780
Tons of ways to diagnose it,

144
00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:33.600
and blood eosinophilia may help support the diagnosis.

145
00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:37.150
Here's a picture of the erythema nodosum

146
00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:40.230
on the bilateral lower legs of this patient.

147
00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:42.980
It's an inflammation of the subcutaneous fat, actually.

148
00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:48.960
Now, there's no evidence from randomized clinical trials

149
00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:50.490
to determine whether antifungal treatment

150
00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:53.490
for uncomplicated cocci infections reduces symptom duration

151
00:06:53.490 --> 00:06:54.600
or prevents complications.

152
00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:58.050
But as I mentioned, there's a current prospective trial

153
00:06:58.050 --> 00:06:59.640
that the government is doing right now

154
00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:03.180
about treating these patients with fluconazole treatment.

155
00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:05.550
And the guess is by infectious disease

156
00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:07.950
that it's gonna make a difference.

157
00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:10.650
In any case, you should institute treatment

158
00:07:10.650 --> 00:07:13.143
in anyone who is at higher risk.

159
00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:16.830
These patients are not contagious,

160
00:07:16.830 --> 00:07:18.420
you can follow their disease progress

161
00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:20.490
with complement fixation titers.

162
00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:21.900
Some recommend treatment if the titer

163
00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:23.463
is greater than 1 to 16,

164
00:07:24.810 --> 00:07:27.303
less than 1 to 4 is a better prognosis.

165
00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:31.710
Complications, this was also asked of me on the boards.

166
00:07:31.710 --> 00:07:35.340
Possible complications are meningitis

167
00:07:35.340 --> 00:07:38.850
and an infectious monoarthritis.

168
00:07:38.850 --> 00:07:40.050
if you're going to treat,

169
00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:42.930
it's likely going to be fluconazole,

170
00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:46.263
400 milligrams once a day for 3 to 12 months.

171
00:07:49.230 --> 00:07:52.440
Now, this is off the CDC's website.

172
00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:55.470
They use the term cocci when talking about

173
00:07:55.470 --> 00:07:57.120
coccidioidomycosis.

174
00:07:57.120 --> 00:07:58.950
So the acronym here is, number one,

175
00:07:58.950 --> 00:08:01.143
consider the diagnosis, think about it.

176
00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:03.690
Number two, order the right tests.

177
00:08:03.690 --> 00:08:06.600
Number three, check for risk factors,

178
00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:09.780
check for complications, and then initiate management.

179
00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:11.913
So this is our algorithm for cocci.

180
00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:16.500
All right, I would definitely know those slides

181
00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:19.560
'cause I'm suspecting you're gonna get asked questions.

182
00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:21.780
Now we're gonna move along to tuberculosis,

183
00:08:21.780 --> 00:08:24.240
and I guarantee there's gonna be questions on TB as well,

184
00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:28.080
they love to ask all manner of, in my opinion,

185
00:08:28.080 --> 00:08:31.650
very tricky questions about tuberculosis.

186
00:08:31.650 --> 00:08:34.980
So this is infection with mycobacterium to TB.

187
00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:36.690
Several factors determine the risk.

188
00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:37.920
These are important.

189
00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:40.080
So the infectiousness of the source patient,

190
00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:41.730
how many bacteria are they spewing?

191
00:08:41.730 --> 00:08:43.860
How susceptible is the host?

192
00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:45.940
How long is the exposure

193
00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:49.200
and the environment of the exposure?

194
00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:50.790
Again, small spaces

195
00:08:50.790 --> 00:08:54.450
with poor ventilation confer the highest risk, right?

196
00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.010
And then lastly, the infectiousness

197
00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:58.473
of the particular MTB strain.

198
00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:02.700
Now, patients with TB,

199
00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:04.770
they can go anywhere from active tuberculosis,

200
00:09:04.770 --> 00:09:06.510
we call that TB disease,

201
00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:08.880
anywhere to those infected with no clinical disease,

202
00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:12.303
we call that latent TB infection or LTBI.

203
00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:15.630
And here's the guidelines

204
00:09:15.630 --> 00:09:19.470
from the Infectious Disease Society of America from 2017,

205
00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:20.490
that was the latest update.

206
00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:22.800
Who should be tested for TB?

207
00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:24.300
The goal is to identify patients

208
00:09:24.300 --> 00:09:25.590
who would benefit from therapy.

209
00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:26.423
So that's not everyone,

210
00:09:26.423 --> 00:09:28.770
everyone doesn't need to be tested for TB.

211
00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:30.960
If you're at low risk, you probably don't need it.

212
00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:33.090
Higher risk patient,

213
00:09:33.090 --> 00:09:35.790
if you live with someone who has TB,

214
00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:36.930
you're immune suppressed,

215
00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:39.180
you're from a country where it's common,

216
00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:43.020
occupational or social situations like nursing homes,

217
00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:44.250
healthcare providers,

218
00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:47.280
obviously, if we care for TB patients,

219
00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:48.630
use of illicit substances,

220
00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:50.780
and don't forget about those with symptoms.

221
00:09:51.690 --> 00:09:53.010
You got two options for testing.

222
00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:55.440
There's the traditional skin test,

223
00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:56.430
that's the injection

224
00:09:56.430 --> 00:10:00.690
of purified protein derivative subcutaneously.

225
00:10:00.690 --> 00:10:02.070
And then the newer kid on the block

226
00:10:02.070 --> 00:10:04.980
is the Interferon-Gamma Release Assay,

227
00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:07.050
usually the QuantiFERON Gold,

228
00:10:07.050 --> 00:10:09.000
and that's a blood test.

229
00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:10.920
Now if you're gonna do the skin test,

230
00:10:10.920 --> 00:10:14.400
remember you're looking for induration, not erythema.

231
00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:16.440
Induration is elevated skin,

232
00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:19.020
and you're gonna read this in 2 to 3 days,

233
00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:20.920
you're gonna record it in millimeters.

234
00:10:22.680 --> 00:10:26.100
A positive test can be read accurately for up to seven days.

235
00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:28.923
Negative tests are only good for three days.

236
00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:31.710
These are what I call the money slides.

237
00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:33.990
These are the slides you should memorize for the boards.

238
00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:36.840
These are the slides that you might get asked a question.

239
00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:40.500
So if they have five millimeters or more of induration,

240
00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:43.650
that's considered positive in these situations.

241
00:10:43.650 --> 00:10:46.260
I live with someone who has tuberculosis.

242
00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:48.120
I've got clinical or radiographic evidence

243
00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:51.213
of current or prior TB or I'm immunosuppressed.

244
00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:55.980
Look at that, immunosuppression.

245
00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:58.260
Not only HIV seropositive patients

246
00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:00.180
and organ transplant recipients,

247
00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:01.980
your rheumatologic patients

248
00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:04.710
who might be on prednisone 15 milligrams a day

249
00:11:04.710 --> 00:11:08.430
or on tumor necrosis factor alpha antagonist.

250
00:11:08.430 --> 00:11:10.620
There's a lot of those patients out there.

251
00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:14.940
Even your patients coming from dermatology

252
00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:17.370
because they've got a psoriasis,

253
00:11:17.370 --> 00:11:19.830
there's a lot of uses for these biologics now.

254
00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:22.350
So in those cases, five millimeters or more

255
00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:24.660
is considered positive result.

256
00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:27.090
10 is positive if they're a recent immigrant

257
00:11:27.090 --> 00:11:28.320
from a high-risk country,

258
00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:30.030
they live in a high-prevalence area,

259
00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:32.880
they have diabetes, renal failure, or cancer,

260
00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:36.690
they're a long-term care facility resident or employee,

261
00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:38.880
a prison inmate, an IV drug user,

262
00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:43.443
young children, or those working in a mycobacteriology lab.

263
00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:46.590
And then for the rest of us it's 15 millimeters,

264
00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:47.610
so that's pretty much anyone else

265
00:11:47.610 --> 00:11:49.530
including healthcare workers.

266
00:11:49.530 --> 00:11:52.050
Pros and cons to IGRAs:

267
00:11:52.050 --> 00:11:53.910
They're more sensitive and specific.

268
00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:56.580
They are now recommended by the CDC.

269
00:11:56.580 --> 00:11:58.380
There are fewer false positives.

270
00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:00.960
They're preferred overall.

271
00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:03.210
The negative is it's a blood study

272
00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:04.770
and they have to be processed

273
00:12:04.770 --> 00:12:05.850
within a certain amount of hours,

274
00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:07.770
they're gonna be more expensive.

275
00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:08.670
But you don't have to come back

276
00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:10.410
in 2 or 3 days and haven't looked at either.

277
00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:11.700
So I give my patients the option,

278
00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:12.800
which one do you want?

279
00:12:13.830 --> 00:12:17.403
Now, guidelines for the diagnosis of latent TB infection,

280
00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:22.710
the IGRA is recommended over the skin test now

281
00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:24.330
and anyone above the age of five

282
00:12:24.330 --> 00:12:25.740
who are likely to be infected

283
00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:28.470
have low to moderate risk of disease progression.

284
00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:29.940
Testing is warranted,

285
00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:32.700
and they either have a history of BCG vaccination

286
00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:35.730
or they're unlikely to return for their skin test.

287
00:12:35.730 --> 00:12:37.050
These are all the times

288
00:12:37.050 --> 00:12:39.540
where you should reach for the IGRA.

289
00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:43.683
Overall, it is recommended over the skin test.

290
00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:50.330
Okay, people at low risk for TB don't need to be tested.

291
00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:52.200
If you're gonna do testing

292
00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:53.370
in these low risk groups,

293
00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:55.710
the IGRA is recommended.

294
00:12:55.710 --> 00:12:57.810
And then if the initial test is positive,

295
00:12:57.810 --> 00:12:59.370
you're gonna do a second diagnostic test,

296
00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:00.690
you wanna repeat the test.

297
00:13:00.690 --> 00:13:04.593
And the repeat test could be the IGRA or the skin test.

298
00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:09.810
All right, what about TB disease?

299
00:13:09.810 --> 00:13:12.150
This is a patient with active tuberculosis.

300
00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:14.460
This could be suspected based on pulmonary imaging

301
00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:16.110
or your screening tests.

302
00:13:16.110 --> 00:13:18.390
You're gonna do a CT.

303
00:13:18.390 --> 00:13:21.060
Send 'em into the radiology department, let's get a CT.

304
00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:23.190
You can get active TB or prior TB

305
00:13:23.190 --> 00:13:25.683
and they have different appearances.

306
00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:29.313
The boards would make it pretty obvious.

307
00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:33.390
Okay, next question.

308
00:13:33.390 --> 00:13:35.220
We have a different case now.

309
00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:36.960
We have a 42-year-old

310
00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:39.210
recent immigrant from Cambodia

311
00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:42.060
who presents with a one month history of cough,

312
00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:44.070
night sweats, and weight loss.

313
00:13:44.070 --> 00:13:47.460
Their PPD is positive at 14 millimeters

314
00:13:47.460 --> 00:13:48.660
and the chest X-ray reveals

315
00:13:48.660 --> 00:13:50.970
a left upper lobe cavitary lesion.

316
00:13:50.970 --> 00:13:54.660
Induced sputum smear shows acid-fast bacilli.

317
00:13:54.660 --> 00:13:55.530
Which one of the following

318
00:13:55.530 --> 00:13:57.633
is the most appropriate initial therapy?

319
00:13:58.470 --> 00:14:02.940
So, this is one

320
00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:04.860
of these board questions

321
00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:06.780
where you need to know what the diagnosis is,

322
00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:09.300
and then you need to know the treatment.

323
00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:11.220
In this case, it's pretty obvious he's got TB, right?

324
00:14:11.220 --> 00:14:12.900
So what are we gonna do?

325
00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.690
A: Isoniazid monotherapy.

326
00:14:15.690 --> 00:14:18.690
B: INH and ethambutol.

327
00:14:18.690 --> 00:14:21.540
C: INH, ethambutol, and pyrazinamide.

328
00:14:21.540 --> 00:14:26.160
Or D: INH, ethambutol, pyrazinamide, and rifampin.

329
00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:29.433
What do we like for treating tuberculosis initially?

330
00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:33.363
The most appropriate initial therapy is the STEM set.

331
00:14:39.690 --> 00:14:42.360
Good, the majority of you throw the kitchen sink at 'em

332
00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:43.890
till you figure out what's going on.

333
00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:45.780
And then based on cultures,

334
00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:47.670
you might refine that therapy,

335
00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:49.883
but initially you're gonna throw the kitchen sink.

336
00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:54.947
So once weekly, isoniazid and rifapentine

337
00:14:54.947 --> 00:14:58.740
for 12 weeks is now recommended over isoniazid

338
00:14:58.740 --> 00:15:01.320
for nine months for latent TB infection.

339
00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:04.110
Please memorize that if you don't already know it.

340
00:15:04.110 --> 00:15:07.560
This is a change from the previous guidelines.

341
00:15:07.560 --> 00:15:10.740
For latent TB, so they don't have active TB

342
00:15:10.740 --> 00:15:12.363
but they tested positive,

343
00:15:14.250 --> 00:15:16.437
we need once weekly is isoniazid

344
00:15:16.437 --> 00:15:19.440
and rifapentine for 12 weeks.

345
00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:20.850
That is the new recommendation

346
00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:23.160
over isoniazid for nine months.

347
00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:25.380
You can do self-administered therapy

348
00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:27.390
or directly observe therapy.

349
00:15:27.390 --> 00:15:30.390
They also recommend doing video conferencing

350
00:15:30.390 --> 00:15:31.950
to be sure that the patient's taking their pill

351
00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:34.263
as well, increases efficacy.

352
00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:38.460
Now, with TB disease,

353
00:15:38.460 --> 00:15:40.560
you wanna do aggressive combination therapy.

354
00:15:40.560 --> 00:15:42.780
Your intensive phase for two months

355
00:15:42.780 --> 00:15:46.107
is INH, rifampin, ethambutol, and pyrazinamide.

356
00:15:46.107 --> 00:15:48.240
And then your continuation phase

357
00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:52.503
for an additional four months would be INH and rifampin.

358
00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:55.140
Don't forget about supplementing

359
00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:57.753
with B6 in your patients taking isoniazid.

360
00:15:59.580 --> 00:16:01.200
Post-treatment follow up.

361
00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:03.270
They don't need to be retested with a skin test.

362
00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:05.430
They need to have documentation about what was tested,

363
00:16:05.430 --> 00:16:07.170
how they were tested,

364
00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:09.180
educate them about their symptoms, et cetera.

365
00:16:09.180 --> 00:16:10.950
That's fairly obvious.

366
00:16:10.950 --> 00:16:12.187
All right, next question.

367
00:16:12.187 --> 00:16:16.380
"Which work site exposures confer the greatest risk

368
00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:18.420
of lung cancer among those workers

369
00:16:18.420 --> 00:16:20.790
who develop an occupational lung disease

370
00:16:20.790 --> 00:16:23.370
due to their exposure?"

371
00:16:23.370 --> 00:16:26.370
So, is it A: Construction sites,

372
00:16:26.370 --> 00:16:29.250
B: Factories, C: Farms,

373
00:16:29.250 --> 00:16:32.610
D: Mines or stone quarries?

374
00:16:32.610 --> 00:16:36.870
One of these has the highest occupational risk

375
00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:39.060
for lung cancer.

376
00:16:39.060 --> 00:16:41.613
I was asked this question on the boards as well,

377
00:16:43.950 --> 00:16:45.500
so that's why I've included it.

378
00:16:46.560 --> 00:16:47.960
All right, what do we think?

379
00:16:54.660 --> 00:16:56.070
Okay, learning opportunity,

380
00:16:56.070 --> 00:16:58.470
construction sites is the answer here.

381
00:16:58.470 --> 00:17:01.220
I see where you're coming from with the stone quarries,

382
00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:05.640
that it could be a tricky question actually,

383
00:17:05.640 --> 00:17:06.750
the way I answered it.

384
00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:11.750
Anyway, asbestos confers the highest risk

385
00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:15.900
for lung cancer among patients

386
00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:18.720
with occupational lung disease,

387
00:17:18.720 --> 00:17:22.230
so those who breathe in asbestos.

388
00:17:22.230 --> 00:17:25.680
Now, with idiopathic with pulmonary fibrosis

389
00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:29.490
and other diseases, silicosis is a huge problem,

390
00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:30.930
so in your stone quarries.

391
00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:34.440
But for lung cancer, it's asbestosis,

392
00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:36.783
which is generally in construction workers.

393
00:17:37.860 --> 00:17:39.720
Patients who work in farms

394
00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:42.390
are exposed to bio dusts and aerosols,

395
00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:44.940
doesn't increase the risk of lung cancer.

396
00:17:44.940 --> 00:17:48.300
Factory workers who have chemical pneumonitis, same.

397
00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:52.927
Silicosis definitely can cause chronic lung diseases,

398
00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:55.980
interstitial lung diseases,

399
00:17:55.980 --> 00:17:59.523
but it's less risky as far as the lung cancer risk.

400
00:18:01.350 --> 00:18:04.710
There will be some question on occupational lung diseases

401
00:18:04.710 --> 00:18:07.530
in some regard on the exam,

402
00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:10.200
it's hard to say which way they'll go.

403
00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:12.510
All right, so I'm rounding things out here.

404
00:18:12.510 --> 00:18:14.010
Pulmonary hypertension,

405
00:18:14.010 --> 00:18:17.280
I really didn't know if I should put this in here or not.

406
00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:19.170
It's technically an elevated blood pressure

407
00:18:19.170 --> 00:18:20.553
in the pulmonary arteries.

408
00:18:21.540 --> 00:18:23.190
But Dr. Firnhaber doesn't talk about it

409
00:18:23.190 --> 00:18:26.850
in hypertension, so I've included it here,

410
00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:29.880
primarily because many times

411
00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:34.880
the risks can be pulmonary.

412
00:18:34.890 --> 00:18:38.820
Patients with COPD, patients with silicosis,

413
00:18:38.820 --> 00:18:40.140
these patients can go on

414
00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:43.050
to develop pulmonary artery hypertension,

415
00:18:43.050 --> 00:18:46.200
which of course narrows the pulmonary arteries,

416
00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:49.950
and it's harder for the right ventricle

417
00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:51.810
to pump the blood through them,

418
00:18:51.810 --> 00:18:54.540
so then the right ventricle eventually fails.

419
00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:56.790
So right heart failure can happen

420
00:18:56.790 --> 00:18:59.760
as a result of pulmonary hypertension,

421
00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:02.760
which can happen from chronic pulmonary diseases.

422
00:19:02.760 --> 00:19:03.593
You follow me?

423
00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:06.210
So that's kind of the thinking

424
00:19:06.210 --> 00:19:08.580
behind why we've included this here

425
00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:11.883
and the way the boards might ask that type of a question.

426
00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:14.640
Therapy is supportive,

427
00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:16.050
it can be a life-threatening situation,

428
00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:17.790
there's really no treatment.

429
00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:21.030
But they're using vasodilators and other agents.

430
00:19:21.030 --> 00:19:24.390
There are five groups of pulmonary artery hypertension.

431
00:19:24.390 --> 00:19:27.180
Group 1 is pretty much idiopathic,

432
00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.520
that could be a genetic factor.

433
00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:31.620
Group 2 comes from left-sided heart failure,

434
00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:33.243
that's actually the most common.

435
00:19:34.110 --> 00:19:37.770
Group 3 is pulmonary hypertension

436
00:19:37.770 --> 00:19:40.500
due to chronic lung diseases or hypoxia.

437
00:19:40.500 --> 00:19:45.500
4 is due to chronic thromboembolic diseases.

438
00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:49.473
And 5 is unclear or multifactorial.

439
00:19:50.370 --> 00:19:55.370
That one also includes sarcoidosis.

440
00:19:56.910 --> 00:19:59.223
Okay, the workup can be extensive, obviously.

441
00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:01.890
All right, we mentioned this earlier.

442
00:20:01.890 --> 00:20:03.150
Moving on to another topic:

443
00:20:03.150 --> 00:20:05.460
Chronic Adult Cough of Unknown Etiology.

444
00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:06.360
This is someone who's coughing

445
00:20:06.360 --> 00:20:07.650
for eight weeks or more,

446
00:20:07.650 --> 00:20:09.600
not sure if it's voluntary or involuntary,

447
00:20:09.600 --> 00:20:10.833
but they're doing it.

448
00:20:12.450 --> 00:20:13.890
As I said, you can get these

449
00:20:13.890 --> 00:20:15.720
from the lung parenchyma itself.

450
00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:18.300
You can get them from sinus drainage down,

451
00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:21.240
or you can get them from gastroesophageal reflux up.

452
00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:24.120
That's how I like to think of these anatomically.

453
00:20:24.120 --> 00:20:25.200
If they're on an ACE inhibitor,

454
00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:26.460
switch 'em to an ARB.

455
00:20:26.460 --> 00:20:28.230
Smokers should quit.

456
00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:31.350
You're probably gonna do pulmonary function testing

457
00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:33.540
and a chest X-ray.

458
00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:35.610
The most common causes of chronic cough

459
00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:38.283
are upper airway cough syndrome,

460
00:20:39.270 --> 00:20:41.133
cough variant asthma,

461
00:20:42.120 --> 00:20:44.640
or gastroesophageal reflux disease,

462
00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:46.353
either alone or in combination.

463
00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:50.130
But this is a common problem

464
00:20:50.130 --> 00:20:51.980
that we contend with in primary care.

465
00:20:53.130 --> 00:20:54.360
The upper airway cough syndrome

466
00:20:54.360 --> 00:20:55.590
is probably the most common.

467
00:20:55.590 --> 00:20:57.540
So this is sinus drainage down,

468
00:20:57.540 --> 00:20:58.840
they could have allergies.

469
00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:01.500
I will tell you personally,

470
00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:04.260
since I've been down here in Dallas,

471
00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:06.390
my allergies have been acting up a bit.

472
00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:08.580
So I've got a little bit of sinus drainage as well

473
00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:11.790
from the allergens here,

474
00:21:11.790 --> 00:21:15.690
because the allergen season,

475
00:21:15.690 --> 00:21:17.850
you've got four allergy seasons.

476
00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:19.800
You've got spring, summer, fall, and winter.

477
00:21:19.800 --> 00:21:23.115
Spring is tree pollen, and it depends on where you live.

478
00:21:23.115 --> 00:21:25.890
In Detroit, our trees aren't pollinating yet,

479
00:21:25.890 --> 00:21:27.270
it hasn't been warm enough.

480
00:21:27.270 --> 00:21:29.310
In Dallas, obviously they are.

481
00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:30.860
In the summer you've got grass pollen.

482
00:21:30.860 --> 00:21:32.340
In the fall it's ragweed.

483
00:21:32.340 --> 00:21:36.030
And in the winter, it's dust and indoor allergens, right?

484
00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:37.683
All of these can cause a cough.

485
00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:41.760
So if you suspect this is what's going on,

486
00:21:41.760 --> 00:21:44.700
put 'em on saline irrigation, maybe a decongestion,

487
00:21:44.700 --> 00:21:47.430
and then antihistamines, and nasal steroids.

488
00:21:47.430 --> 00:21:48.750
Antihistamines and nasal steroids

489
00:21:48.750 --> 00:21:50.400
are a very effective combination.

490
00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:52.923
Cough-variant asthma,

491
00:21:54.270 --> 00:21:56.730
very common to see asthma

492
00:21:56.730 --> 00:21:59.190
where they don't have wheezing or dyspnea,

493
00:21:59.190 --> 00:22:00.690
but they just have the cough.

494
00:22:00.690 --> 00:22:02.580
It's not uncommon with asthma at all.

495
00:22:02.580 --> 00:22:05.040
And those patients respond very well

496
00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:06.693
to inhaled corticosteroids.

497
00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:11.430
Also non-asthmatic eosinophilic bronchitis.

498
00:22:11.430 --> 00:22:13.230
Dr. Holt was asked this question

499
00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:14.730
and she asked me about it earlier.

500
00:22:14.730 --> 00:22:16.560
The treatment there focuses again

501
00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:18.213
on inhaled corticosteroids.

502
00:22:19.530 --> 00:22:21.180
Gastroesophageal reflux disease,

503
00:22:21.180 --> 00:22:25.560
you get acid reflux up that irritates the esophagus.

504
00:22:25.560 --> 00:22:28.500
It's interesting if you take a stomach acid,

505
00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:30.600
hydrochloric acid, and I have a vial of it,

506
00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:34.410
and I pour the vial out on this table.

507
00:22:34.410 --> 00:22:36.450
Of course the liquid would eventually start eating

508
00:22:36.450 --> 00:22:38.640
through the tablecloth and the table,

509
00:22:38.640 --> 00:22:39.990
but it doesn't stop there.

510
00:22:39.990 --> 00:22:44.520
You get these clouds

511
00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:46.743
that kind of just move and waft along,

512
00:22:48.570 --> 00:22:50.700
and the same thing happens inside the body

513
00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:52.830
when you have reflux of the stomach acid,

514
00:22:52.830 --> 00:22:54.270
whether it's the actual acid

515
00:22:54.270 --> 00:22:55.650
or the vapors of the acid

516
00:22:55.650 --> 00:22:57.840
can irritate the sinuses in the throat

517
00:22:57.840 --> 00:23:00.300
and cause chronic sore throat or chronic cough.

518
00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:01.530
So the easiest solution there,

519
00:23:01.530 --> 00:23:02.790
put 'em on two weeks of a trial

520
00:23:02.790 --> 00:23:04.650
of a proton-pump inhibitor.

521
00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:06.450
Every pharmacy in the country now

522
00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:09.360
sells these little bottles of 14 pills

523
00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:12.450
of Prilosec or Nexium,

524
00:23:12.450 --> 00:23:16.140
because we do a two-week trial in outpatient medicine

525
00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:17.640
and see how your symptoms do.

526
00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:18.810
If your symptoms are gone,

527
00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:20.430
we've probably nailed the diagnosis,

528
00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:23.253
and that's easier than doing expensive testing on them,

529
00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:27.900
like EGDs and so forth.

530
00:23:27.900 --> 00:23:31.770
Cough hypersensitivity syndrome.

531
00:23:31.770 --> 00:23:35.910
This is basically a neurologic situation

532
00:23:35.910 --> 00:23:39.690
where the patient probably had some chronic cough,

533
00:23:39.690 --> 00:23:41.190
and then the nerves got irritated,

534
00:23:41.190 --> 00:23:42.810
and now they want to cough all the time

535
00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:45.630
even though there's really no underlying pathology.

536
00:23:45.630 --> 00:23:49.710
So you would treat that as really a neurologic disorder

537
